> Write an original “field report” from an archivist employed by a library that exists outside time and collects things that never happened. The archivist has been assigned to catalogue a recently acquired item: the complete childhood memories of a civilization that was erased before it evolved.  
>  
> Make the report gradually shift from formal, bureaucratic prose into something intimate, uncanny, and emotionally sincere. Include:  
> - a classification number with an inexplicable flaw in it;  
> - three quoted fragments from the memories;  
> - a disagreement in the margins between two previous archivists;  
> - one mundane object that becomes deeply unsettling;  
> - a final sentence that suggests the archivist may now be part of the collection.  
>  
> Do not explain the world outright. Let its rules emerge indirectly through precise details.

